John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
Scotland’s independent schools have many great academic achievements behind them, and it’s continued in 2018 with yet another series of outstanding exam results, which are further enhanced by individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other community endeavors.
With up to 30,000 students around Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
The independent schools are trying to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can put together and implement a tailored curriculum, we find that modern languages remain a popular topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it hits his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it hits the heart."
It’s an important reminder that we can’t just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust among people from other countries.
We can see from the latest exam results this year that languages are highest in the statistics with the most passed exams in the independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages received the high grade A.
The data collected by SCIS' 74 member schools showed that 72 percent of students received an A grade in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language is now perceived as a topic choice at the same level as STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) subjects in independent schools’ curricula and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that among the reasons why employers were unable to fill vacancies, 17% had a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more important in preparing young people for their future careers.
More job opportunities in the future will require language skills, and these skills are essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career the young people choose, if they have learned another language, they have a great advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person a head start to the competition.
According to a YouGov poll of more than 4,000 people in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to carry on a conversation, and French is the only language spoken by a multi-digit percentage, 15 percent.
Therefore, it is important to invest in language education for those who are children today.
Being able to speak more languages, especially languages from developing countries, gives children a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, schools differ in the languages taught.
A number of schools focus on the more classic modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be most important to the UK looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter what your child is interested in, there will always be a variety of languages to choose from at independent schools with teachers who are specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills required to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At present, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be truly important for the country’s future in a global business environment, and this must be reflected in the degree programmes.
Modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this distinction to Scotland’s youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
