“We have not seen a similar reaction from the United States,” he said.
"Without confidence in the United States, there is no confidence in our national security and under such conditions, there is no chance that we ourselves will take the first step and disarm unilaterally."
While Ri reiterated well-known North Korean grievances about Washington’s opposition to a “phased” approach to nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea would be rewarded if they took gradual steps. But his speech seemed important as it did not unequivocally reject unilateral disarmament, as has otherwise been the case from Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim promised to work “nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea’s security.
North Korea has called for a formal end to the Korean War, which took place in 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also shown opposition to softening up tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘nuclear disarmament first,’ adding to the pressure with sanctions to achieve their purposes by force, and even opposing the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a pipe dream among people who don’t know who we are.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions reinforce our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for a summit between Kim and Trump, as the US leader highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
The minister instead highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding, “If nuclear disarmament were to be negotiated with South Korea and not the United States, the negotiations would not be so deadlocked.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ris’ speech was very different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that firing North Korea’s rockets at the US mainland was inevitable after “Mr Evil President” Trump called Kim a “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
Last year, Trump threatened at the UN with the “total annihilation” of North Korea, but this year he praised Kim for his courage in disarmament, but said there is still much to be done and that sanctions must remain until North Korea disarms.
