Students at Harvard Take Course on Getting Enough Sleep
A new course at Harvard University has given all undergraduate students more sleep. The purpose of the course is to counteract the growing macho culture where you study all night sustained by large amounts of caffeine.
One researcher has shown that students at the world’s best university often don’t know the first thing about taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, has completed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea for the course after giving a presentation on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“When the paper was finished, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told this now that I’m on the candidate list?’
"She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, offered for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleeping habits can improve one’s academic and sporting performance as well as one’s overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health department, says the university has decided to offer the course after finding out that students were in severe sleep deprivation during the week.
Among other things, the hour-long course consists of various interactive exercises.
In one of the exercises, there is a picture of a dorm room where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, running shoes and books to get knowledge about the effects of caffeine and light, and how one’s sporting performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and how important good sleeping habits are.
In another part of the course, participants hear about how sleep deprivation over a long period of time increases the risk of heart attacks, blood clots, depression and cancer.
Participants are encouraged to think about their daily habits by clicking on various icons on an interactive map of the campus.
"We know that this will not change the behaviour of the students immediately.
But we think they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know how cigarettes affect health," adds Professor Czeisler.
The pride that is in taking an “allnighter” still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and increased pressure on students have meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
The “secret weapon” against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety is good and adequate sleep, he said — it even counteracts weight gain because sleep deprivation makes the brain think you’re starving, which is why they’re constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, last year helped Professor Czeisler organize the course when he took one of his courses in his freshman year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and had him work on making it a general course throughout the university.
He hopes that next, all graduates will be offered a similar course before continuing their education.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm so that they know when to go to bed and when to get up. This can create awareness of the harmful effects of the light from electronic screens, which can shift the circadian rhythm and make it harder to fall asleep.
