Yearbook: The Inventor of the Geiger Counter
And now a page from the yearbook "Sunday Morning": The 30th of September, 1882, 136 years ago today – if we count... – was the day when the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger invented a method to detect and measure radioactivity, an invention that would eventually lead to the apparatus known as the Geiger counter.
The Geiger counter has become an integral part of both science and popular culture, as seen in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", in which Roy Rogers and Dale Evans starred as peasant scientists:
Man: "What in the world is that?"
Rogers: “It’s a Geiger counter, which is used to find radioactive minerals such as uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms that the radioactivity in the minerals is making."
Evans: "Oh, come on, it's on!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days before he would have turned 63.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
New cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to "see" cancer cells
New cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to 'see' cancer cells and kill them
Vaccine Teaches Immune System to Recognize Cancer Cells as Part of Treatment
The method consists of extracting immune cells from a patient and altering them in the laboratory
They can then "see" the protein that is common to many cancers and where they are injected again
A test vaccine holds promise in patients with a number of cancers.
When a woman with ovarian cancer was treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize cancer cells, the cancer disappeared for more than 18 months.
